{
  "texts": [
    "It leads to fast rates in the spirit of Theorem 4.3, but with different assumptions (in particular, the X i 's are not random there).",
    "A note on the terminology: a huge number of statistical and machine learning results mentioned above rely on tools from information theory: Zhang (2006) actually proves beautiful PAC-Bayesian bounds under the name \"information theoretic bounds\" (maybe for this reason, it's not always listed with the other PAC-Bayes bounds in the publications on the topic).",
    "My goal here is not to classify what should be called \"PAC-Bayes\" and what should not, I'm certainly not qualified for that.",
    "I simply want to point out the connection to two families of methods inspired directly from information theory.",
    "In Rissanen's Minimum Description Length (MDL) principle, the idea is to penalize the empirical error of a classifier by its shortest description (Rissanen, 1978)."
  ]
}